            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">1 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgPhoenician\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPhoenician', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Phoenician text displayed in the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite0> ).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Understanding Texts: Playing with Consonants and Vowels - An interactive game to understand how syllables are created. (<htcite17>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">2 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgBanner\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgBanner', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Banner in a style similar to that found in Wu Zetian's (武則天) tomb. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite1>).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">3 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgAtra\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgAtra', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Babilonia Tablet Babilónico about the flood. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite2>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Atlas: The Origin of the Universe - Our current understanding of the evolution of the universe and the view people had of it millennia ago. (<htcite18>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Do literature and science not communicate? - Literature offers texts full of abstractions, dreams, and desires, while science is often regarded as objective. This is a common conclusion, but an incorrect one. In this text, we observe that science also contains abstractions and that epics may include descriptions of natural events, even while conveying spectacular ideas that may seem impossible to have occurred or truths presented as unquestionable. (<htcite19>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Has there never been a flood? - There have been several; after all, for a flood to occur, it is enough for torrential rains to cause major disasters. (<htcite34>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: What is the extent of the impact of the flood? - First, it is necessary to determine when it supposedly occurred. Considering that one of the characters, Gilgamesh, was a historical king, it is possible to estimate the period in which he lived and compare it with other places in the world at that time. Clearly, neither Egypt nor Peru were affected by the events described in Tablet XI of what is now known as the <i>Epic of Gilgamesh</i> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('bab0a6a1-d2a4-46b3-8d86-f33e3ad035d6'); return false;\">The British Museum</a>):</p><p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/BritishMuseum/mid_00107404_001.jpg\" id=\"imgGilgamesh\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgGilgamesh', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: The Flood Tablet. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('bab0a6a1-d2a4-46b3-8d86-f33e3ad035d6'); return false;\">The British Museum</a>).</p> (<htcite32>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">4 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgBuda\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgBuda', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">The Flood Tablet. © Trustees of the British Museum ().</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">5 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgBritishMuseum0\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgBritishMuseum0', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Oblong basket of woven reed. © Trustees of the British Museum (). Shared under a <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</a>.</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">6 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgGilgamesh\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgGilgamesh', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Abydos King List. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite3>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Family: Sumerians - Geographic presentation of where the Sumerian peoples were located. (<htcite17>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Do literature and science not communicate? - Literature offers texts full of abstractions, dreams, and desires, while science is often regarded as objective. This is a common conclusion, but an incorrect one. In this text, we observe that science also contains abstractions and that epics may include descriptions of natural events, even while conveying spectacular ideas that may seem impossible to have occurred or truths presented as unquestionable. (<htcite19>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Has there never been a flood? - There have been several; after all, for a flood to occur, it is enough for torrential rains to cause major disasters. (<htcite34>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Is it possible to live in the sky? Is the Earth flat? - <p>Our knowledge in different fields has developed over time. In ancient times, the scattering of light in the atmosphere was mistaken for the sky itself. Since going beyond the atmosphere was unimaginable, human thought projected the possibility of building something to reach the 'sky' or even to live in it. After millennia of study, we know that ancient texts reflected the knowledge of their time or, at best, were metaphorical writings.</p><p>Similarly, the shape of the Earth was also unknown in antiquity. It was only in <htdate0> that the Earth’s sphericity was demonstrated. Even so, due to certain fictions, some people returned to believing it might be flat. Additional details can be found in the <i>Atlas</i> section (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('f140d8d6-80cc-4d82-b9f7-c3ba06bf2ed3'); return false;\">History Tracers Team, <htdate1>, Atlas</a>).</p> (<htcite31>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: What is the extent of the impact of the flood? - First, it is necessary to determine when it supposedly occurred. Considering that one of the characters, Gilgamesh, was a historical king, it is possible to estimate the period in which he lived and compare it with other places in the world at that time. Clearly, neither Egypt nor Peru were affected by the events described in Tablet XI of what is now known as the <i>Epic of Gilgamesh</i> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('bab0a6a1-d2a4-46b3-8d86-f33e3ad035d6'); return false;\">The British Museum</a>):</p><p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/BritishMuseum/mid_00107404_001.jpg\" id=\"imgGilgamesh\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgGilgamesh', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: The Flood Tablet. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('bab0a6a1-d2a4-46b3-8d86-f33e3ad035d6'); return false;\">The British Museum</a>).</p> (<htcite32>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">7 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgMid001\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMid001', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Different types of vessels, exhibited at the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite4> ).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>History: Cradles of civilization (Parte II) - We continue our study by exploring the civilizations of Egypt, Indus Valley, and China. (<htcite20>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">8 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgEgypt\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgEgypt', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Cyrus Cylinder. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite5> ).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Understanding Texts: The Writing System - More than just a tool for daily use, the writing system is a milestone that allows us to divide human history into prehistory and recorded events. (<htcite21>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">9 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgPottery1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPottery1', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Map of the Inhabited World. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite6>).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">10 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgCylinder\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCylinder', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Tablet found in Tell Al-'Ubaid. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite7>).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">11 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgB\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgB', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Astrolabe showing a calendar with the months in Latin, held in the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite8> ).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Atlas: Comparing Worlds - Comparison between the world understood by the Babylonians and our current world. (<htcite22>)</li><li>Atlas: The Ancient Babylonian World Map - Babylon: Study of the first known world map. (<htcite23>)</li><li>History: Cradles of civilization (Part I) - While humanity originated in Africa, the first civilizations emerged in various regions around the world, such as Mesopotamia, the Andes, and Mesoamerica. (<htcite24>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Anachronism - although it is a word unknown to many, it is an action frequently practiced. (<htcite25>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Equality Levels - Some concepts, like the definition of a planet, change over time. Sometimes, objects with slightly different sizes can be considered equal. How can we use numbers to quantify equality? (<htcite26>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Did texts written in Mesopotamia describe the world we know today? - To properly answer this question, it is necessary to understand what was meant by 'world' in ancient times. Since the first known world map did not even mention nearby regions, it is not possible to claim that they had any idea of the true size of the world when they referred to their 'known world'. (<htcite33>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Has there never been a flood? - There have been several; after all, for a flood to occur, it is enough for torrential rains to cause major disasters. (<htcite34>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">12 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgT1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgT1', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Tang Dynasty coin from the year <htdate0>, at the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite9> ).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">13 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgAstro\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgAstro', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\"><i>Epic of Lugalbanda</i>. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite10>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Physics: Organizing time - Many cultures organize time into 7-day weeks and months with varying numbers of days (28/29, 30, or 31). Is this division accurate? (<htcite35>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">14 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgCoin\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCoin', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Clay tablet with materials for Magan boats. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite11>).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">15 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgLugalbanda\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgLugalbanda', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Dedicatory cone. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite12>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Family: Sumerians - Geographic presentation of where the Sumerian peoples were located. (<htcite17>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">16 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgMagan\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMagan', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Glass Beads. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite13>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Understanding the Multiplication Table (6 and 7) (First Steps (Volume 1))</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">17 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgCD\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCD', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Cylinder Seal of <i>Meskalamdug</i>. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite14>).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">18 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgGB\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgGB', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Vessel decorated with cord marks, exhibited at the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite15> ).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">19 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgSuanpan\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgSuanpan', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Clovis point projectile exhibited at the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum ( ).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">20 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgC1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgC1', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Arrowhead made from bone, featuring inscriptions. © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite16> ).</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">21 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgBritishMuseum1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgBritishMuseum1', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Prism from Library of Ashurbanipal. © Trustees of the British Museum ().</div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">22 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgPottery\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPottery', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\"></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">23 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgPoint\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPoint', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\"></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">24 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgXuanzong\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgXuanzong', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\"></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">25 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgChinese\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgChinese', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\"></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">26 / 26</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgPBM\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPBM', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\"></div></div><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-left htSlidePrev\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(-1);\"></i><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right htSlideNext\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(1);\"></i></div></p>",
